variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"NARBONNE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Angelle, Charlet, Jean-Paul, Yves.","French: habitational name, with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘from’, denoting someone from either of two places called Arbonne, in Pyrénées-Atlantiques and Seine-et-Marne. This surname is very rare in France.","History: In North America, this surname was originally (also) a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, now found among the descendants of Jean Guyon du Buisson from France (see   Guyon  ), through his grandson François Guyon <i>dit</i> Darbonne, who married Jeanne de la Grande Terre in Natchitoches, LA, in 1725."],"variants":[{"name":"Guyon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gaston, Jean-Francois, Virginie.","French and English: from the Old French personal name <i>Guyon</i>, a pet form of   Guy  . Compare   Dion   3,   Gue  ,   Guion  ,   Yeon   2,   Yon   3, and   Young   4.","History: Jean Guyon du Buisson from Tourouvre in Orne, France, was one of the earliest settlers on the north shore of the St. Lawrence River in New France. He arrived together with his large family in 1634, and is said to be an ancestor of at least three out of four Québécois. Among the surnames borne by his descendants are his surname <i>Guyon</i> and its various altered forms, including <i>Deo(n)</i>, <i>Deyo</i>, <i>Dion</i>, <i>Yéon</i>, <i>Yon</i>, and <i>Young</i>, and also the <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) names   Darbonne   and   Dumontier  , adopted as a surname by two of his grandsons, and the <i>dit</i> name   Lemoine  , adopted by another descendant. — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America. As a Huguenot ancestor is listed Jacques Guyon, who was in NY by 1680. However, his descendants bear only an altered form of the surname,   Gue  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Arsinde de NARBONNE was born on 10 June 1054, in Narbonne, Aude, Occitanie, France. She married Guillaume Amanieu II de Bezaume about 1070, in La Réole, Gironde, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died about 1090, in Saint-Bonnet, Charente, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France, at the age of 37."},"et":{"10 JUN 1054–ABT 1090":"10. juuni 1054–umbes 1090","1040–1103":"1040–1103","–1097":"–1097","–Female":"Surnud","1054–1090":"1054–1090","1090":"1090","1103":"1103","10 JUN 1054":"10. juuni 1054","1054":"1054","1097":"1097","ABT 1090":"umbes 1090","1040":"1040","ABT 1070":"umbes 1070","Saint-Bonnet,16303,Charente,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,FRANCE,":"Saint-Bonnet, Charente, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","La Réole,33352,Gironde,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,FRANCE,":"La Réole, Gironde, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Narbonne,11262,Aude,Occitanie,FRANCE,":"Narbonne, Aude, Occitanie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"10 JUN 1054–ABT 1090":"10. kesäkuuta 1054–noin 1090","1040–1103":"1040–1103","–1097":"–1097","–Female":"Kuollut","1054–1090":"1054–1090","1090":"1090","1103":"1103","10 JUN 1054":"10. kesäkuuta 1054","1054":"1054","1097":"1097","ABT 1090":"noin 1090","1040":"1040","ABT 1070":"noin 1070","Saint-Bonnet,16303,Charente,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,FRANCE,":"Saint-Bonnet, Charente, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Ranska","La Réole,33352,Gironde,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,FRANCE,":"La Réole, Gironde, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Ranska","Narbonne,11262,Aude,Occitanie,FRANCE,":"Narbonne, Aude, Occitanie, Ranska"},"fr":{"10 JUN 1054–ABT 1090":"10 juin 1054–environ 1090","1040–1103":"1040–1